    "(2.16)Then there exists at least one solution (µ, φ, ξ, σ) in the sense of Definition 2.1.",
    "Moreover, if(u 1, u 2) ∈ L 2 (0, T; L 3 (Ω)) × L 2 (Q) (2.17)in addition to (2.16), then the solution is unique.",
    "Furthermore, let(µ i, φ i, ξ i, σ i), i = 1, 2, be two solutions to (1.1)-(1.5) associated with the data (u i 1, u i 2) ∈ L 2 (0, T; L 3 (Ω)) × L 2 (Q), i = 1, 2.Then there exists a constant K 1 > 0, which depends only on the data of the system, such that∥µ 1 -µ 2 ∥ L ∞ (0,T; H) + ∥1 * (µ 1 -µ 2)∥ L ∞ (0,T; V) + ∥φ 1 -φ 2 ∥ L ∞ (0,T; H)∩L 2 (0,T; V) + ∥σ 1 -σ 2 ∥ L ∞ (0,T; H)∩L 2 (0,T; V) ≤ K 1 ∥u 1 1 -u 2 1 ∥ L 2 (0,T; H) + ∥u 1 2 -u 2 2 ∥ L 2 (0,T; H).",
    "(2.18)Before entering the proof, let us remark that the above result is very general and includes also the cases of singular and nonsmooth potentials such as the double obstacle potential defined in (1.8).",
    "We also note that the assumption F 1 (φ 0) ∈ L 1 (Ω) stated in (2.15) actually follows from other requiremens on φ 0 thanks to the subdifferential propertyΩ F 1 (φ 0) ≤ Ω F 1 (v) + ((∂F 1) • (φ 0), φ 0 -v) for every v ∈ H.About the explicit dependencies of the constant K 1 in (2.18), we invite the reader to follow the proof of the estimate given below.Proof."
  ]
